defaultThe Government currently states that it does not provide ‘harmful’ subsidies. Therefore it is impossible to assess if the Government has plans or targets to reduce or eliminate ‘harmful’ subsidies; nor its progress in reducing such ‘harmful’ subsidies.default defaultHowever, the Government has a defaultcommitment to supporting low-carbon growth and adaptation in developing countries, defaultunder which defaultthe Government should seek to identify and eliminate ‘harmful’ subsidies provided in the form of development finance. This includes support to fossil fuel energy projects.default&#xa0;
default6.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe submission by HM Treasury and the Department for Energy and 
defaultClimate Change (DECC) to this i
defaultnquiry
default, states that the UK does not have any ‘harmful’ energy policies, but does not address the 
defaultbroader 
defaultquestion of ‘harmful’ subsidies. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government does not consider that any of its energy policies are ‘harmful’. Furthermore, energy policy (as with other Government policy) is subject to an initial impact assessment and subsequent monitoring, evaluation and review. This ensures that the Government can provide confidence and certainty while ensuring that the policy advances the Government’s objectives in a coherent way that provides best value for money. It also ensures that detrimental consequences can be quickly and effectively addressed.
default&#xa0;
default6.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe HM Trea
defaultsury / DECC submission to this i
defaultnquiry
default defines fossil fuel subsidies as follows:
default&#xa0;
defaultFor the purposes of G20 work on inefficient fossil fuel subsidies, the UK, along with other EU G20 members, defines a fossil fuel subsidy as any Government measure or programme with the objective or direct consequence of reducing, below world-market prices, including all costs of transport, refining and distribution, the effective cost of fossil fuels paid by final consumers, or of reducing the costs or increasing the revenues of fossil-fuel producing companies.
